In C#, attributes allow you to add metadata or additional information to various programming elements, such as classes, methods, properties, and more. You can create your own custom attributes by defining a new attribute class. Here's an example of how to create a custom attribute in C#:

```csharp
using System;

// Define a custom attribute
[AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Class | AttributeTargets.Method, AllowMultiple = false)]
public class MyCustomAttribute : Attribute
{
    public string Name { get; set; }

    public MyCustomAttribute(string name)
    {
        Name = name;
    }
}

// Apply the custom attribute
[MyCustom("Sample")]
public class MyClass
{
    [MyCustom("SomeMethod")]
    public void MyMethod()
    {
        // Method implementation
    }
}
```

In the example above, a custom attribute class `MyCustomAttribute` is defined, which takes a `string` parameter `name` in its constructor. The attribute is then applied to a class (`MyClass`) and a method (`MyMethod`) using the `MyCustom` attribute.

You can access the attributes at runtime using reflection to retrieve the metadata or take specific actions based on the attribute's presence or values.

Keep in mind that custom attributes can be used for various purposes, such as data validation, extending behavior, or providing additional information to other parts of your code.

Note: The `AttributeUsage` attribute applied to `MyCustomAttribute` specifies where the attribute can be applied (`AttributeTargets.Class` and `AttributeTargets.Method`) and whether multiple instances of the attribute can be applied to the same element (`AllowMultiple = false`).
